name: Victorian Anime Art
description:
Got sick and tired of trying to figure out how to get a so-called "Victorian Anime" aesthetic, which I'm enthralled with, so I made a LoRA. Used Counterfeit v 2.5 as the base model. It's my first time making a LoRA, so I have no clue about a lot of things regarding them, but I used 20 images to create this one... probably should add more images later, since I noticed that a great majority of the ones I used were close-up portraits, and not full-body stuff.

Anyway, try it out and see what works!

Monet

Update v 2.0: Saw that Counterfeit ver. 3.0 dropped, so I attempted to update VAA to see if it works well with the new model. Doesn't seem to be the case, as it turns out deep-fried and with a persistent green artifact. But, VAA v 2.0 seems to work nicely with Counterfeit ver. 2.5. Perhaps I should wait for a pruned version of Counterfeit 3.0, and see if VAA will meld with it then.

I typically throw weights to the extreme (2.0 for certain prompts, and 1.0 for VAA) to see what happens. Oddly enough a weight of 1 on VAA doesn't seem to produce bad results for me on Counterfeit ver. 2.5. But I would recommend no more than 0.8 if you're working on a different model.

modelVersions.name: v2.0
modelVersions.description:
Used 49 images, albeit mostly portraits--but still got a couple of full-body images in the LoRA training.

Note: Tried to get VAA to work nicely with Counterfeit ver. 3.0, to no avail; keep getting green artifacts, and the overall aesthetic is lost. However, it seems to still work fine with Counterfeit ver. 2.5.

Base Model is on Counterfeit ver. 2.5, though I also tried using AnyLoRA as a base to see if it would then work on Counterfeit ver. 3.0.... it didn't. Tried reducing the image count, etc, but the green artifacts persisted, so the original iteration of VAA v 2.0 is what is being submitted here.
